Encode ruby scripts as US-ASCII so their binary strings are not UTF-8.

Ruby 2.0 will read these a UTF-8 without a magic comment on top.

By forcing US-ASCII on the script, the binary string literals are then
ASCII-8BIT which we can then access byte by byte.

More #589

Fixes test failing with invalid byte sequence like this:

```
irb(main):01:0> "\xac".force_encoding("UTF-8")[0].ord
ArgumentError: invalid byte sequence in UTF-8
```

We want to do this instead:
```
irb(main):02:0> "\xac".force_encoding("ASCII-8BIT")[0].ord
=> 172
```

Fix code broken on ruby 1.9.3

More #589

Ruby 1.8.7:

irb(main):104:0> "a"[0]
=> 97

Need to use String#ord on 1.9.3+:

irb(main):058:0> "a"[0]
=> "a"
irb(main):059:0> "a"[0].ord
=> 97

Add magic comment for files containing binary string literals.

It's more likely we'll be adding more binary strings to these files so
the magic comment will ensure these don't get converted to UTF-8 in ruby
2.0.

More #589

Use magic comment for binary string literals instead of force_encoding.

force_encoding("ASCII-8BIT") only fixes one string at a time.
Future binary string literals added to these files would need to be forced
to binary.  The #encoding magic comment will fix future strings added to
these files.

More #589
